          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> The four richest Africans hold $57.4B in
            wealth - more than half the continentâ€™s population combined. Over
            the past five years, African billionaires have seen a 56% increase
            in their wealth, and currently control nearly $4T. There is also a
            wide gender wealth gap where men hold three times more wealth than
            women (<a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-jul-25-spotlight-h1-1-the-report?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >the report</a
            >).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The reason:</strong> Africaâ€™s tax structures are nearly
            three times less effective than the global average at redistributing
            wealth. Reliance on consumption taxes like VAT (which applies to
            basic goods and services) forces the poor to spend more on
            essentials, while budget cuts reduce availability to healthcare and
            education. Imposing a modest 1% tax on the wealth and 10% on the
            revenue of the richest could raise $66B each year.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; filter: blur(5px)">
            <strong> The challenge:</strong> Political exclusion plays a key
            role in the cycle of inequality. High entry fees demanded by
            political parties, along with common vote-buying practices,
            effectively keep the poor from running for elections. As a result,
            the wealthy control government decisions and protect their own
            interests.
          </p>
